The adventure starts very well.
You are part of a story whose chief hero, Jack, solves some personal problems by participating in an illegal race through America.
You're on the west coast in San Francisco, and your job is to get to New York first.
This design has some interesting features.
The route consists of 10 stages divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race goes along its own route, and the individual stages take place in a diverse and interesting environment.
So there is no feeling that the game is always the same.
Although the schedule is at the same level as in previous parts of the series, it is a pleasure to look at some of the routes.
Yet, play does not cause strong emotions.
Although driving through the desert, through autumn suburbs, or high in snowy mountains is a pleasure.
In addition, the race is periodically reviving an unusual detail.
For example, in the desert, you enter a sandstorm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, the mountains need to be careful not to fall under the bench.
Individual races are quite orderly.
There's only a few varieties, but that's enough.
For a while you're trying to defeat a few rivals; then you're trying to improve time; or you're competing with one opponent.
Among other things, you are occasionally confronted by the police, which makes your task even more difficult.
The components outside the car are new.
It's just interactive animation where most of Jack's time is running away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's not complicated.
It is surprising that these fragments are much smaller than you could expect (all three to be accurate).
In fact, it turns out that it's good for play, because it's not a problem; given all the above, it's one of the things that makes the game more interesting.
The race model follows previous models.
That means it's no longer something special, but it can't be considered a failure.
If you're looking for a real life simulation, you're gonna have to look elsewhere.
Yet, this model of driving is very appropriate for dynamic races, although better options can be found on the market.
So far it's all very good.
But after a while problems arise.
