Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five public tourist agencies had been able to work in the former Czechoslovakia: ʼedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Since travel to the West was severely limited, the tourist agencies of the time were mainly selling tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
The Czech tourists were thus on vacation to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balton).
The only exception was between 1962 and 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime returned to the West, which placed considerable restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
A major paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel individually to socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovakian citizen wanted to travel on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation from that country was needed; otherwise, no individual travel was possible.
At that time, tourist agencies offered to travel to the West, but they had to either stand in line all night with a sleeping bag or have "good friends" in the agency.
And that was not all.
The currency permit was needed to travel to the West, and it was not issued to politically insecure people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovakian currency was not freely convertible; without monetary authorization it was not possible to obtain money (Western currency) for travel to the West.
The Czechs were most likely to spend their vacations at home, resulting in large numbers of cottages and summer homes, and this practice has been maintained to this day.
Since 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic has thus experienced a real revolution.
While prior to 1989, GDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our journeys, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we no longer realize is that before 1989, we were unable to visit freely the most popular Croatia today, since it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the beginning of 1990, the need to obtain a visa to neighbouring countries in Western Europe had been lifted, resulting in a huge wave of short journeys mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians could not have been filled with travels to the West, everyone wanted to go there for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in tents in parks because their income at the time was not sufficient for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring food of one ' s own (conservatives, salts, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech kroner, and decades later our tourists are finally free to purchase Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income have increased, leading to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has enabled tourism agencies to prepare regular flights by charter airlines; compared with the past, flights are now incredibly cheap because of the ability to order wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs didn't need a visa to visit almost all the developed worlds except the United States, which made our travels even easier.
The next major event in the history of travel since the revolution occurred in 2000, and demand led to a historic first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have taken Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, sending 12 exotic flights from the Czech Republic during the winter.
At present, some 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important development of this period, which symbolizes our development since the revolution, occurred in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the U.S. lifted the need for a visa for Czech tourists, thus becoming a permanent member of the world's most advanced countries.
For the first time in the history of 2008, Czechs had spent more than half of their leave abroad (50.3 per cent); and for the first time in history, they had spent more than 15,000 kroner per person during vacations abroad, including expenses at their destination.
