Easy, we just have to go to Facebook.
"We realized that getting to them was not easy," says Jamie Bartlett, author of the recently published report on European cyber-populism of the British research centre DEMOS.
The amount of personal data available on Facebook is so great, says Bartlett, that researchers could easily use an advertising tool on the site to highlight the necessary demographic group with scientific precision -- what marketing scientists have done for several years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing fans across Europe and then promoted them, but instead of showing a new group or diet product, the ad invited the user to a survey that included questions about their level of education, violence and optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook Bartlett and his colleagues, they were able to interview over 10,000 participants in 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries, even without leaving the office.
"It's a brand new way of doing research," says Bartlett.
Some of the results are less impressive: online right-wing groups are mostly male young people who are not satisfied with immigration.
But all of a sudden, "those who combine their online activity with off-line activity are smarter, more democratic and less aggressive than those who hide behind the monitor."
The DEMOS work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a popular new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends expressed in the Lake, posts on the wall and status updates.
With over 800 million active users adding an average of three records a day, Facebook's “exact information” causes a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the name of the site in its title by 800 per cent over the past five years.
For some researchers, Facebook’s beauty is that it provides an opportunity to study people who are unable to approach on the street with a notebook.
"Early, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them."
"You would have to join a party and they would never have accepted you," Bartlett says.
"Fisbook excludes all this, you address them directly."
Others say that this site could identify and study social health problems.
Mégan Moreno, of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues, found that students who discussed their drinking exploits on Facebook were much more at risk of alcoholism than students who were silent about it.
Moreno suggests that students' peers, such as their hostels, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who too often updates his drinking status.
"You can't solve the problem without discovering it," said Washington Post Demetrius Christakis, co-author of Moreno and Director of the Center for Child Health, Conduct and Development at Seattle Children's Research Institute.
"We found a way to identify children from a risk group that we wouldn't otherwise find."
Facebook also receives various data on its users on a continuous basis.
The site data processing team processed Valentine ' s Relations and Day Statistics, voter turnout in mid-2010, as well as the National Happiness Index (mostly using information that they had only access to - cyber-freedom champions had long insisted that the site should make its extensive collection of data publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not, in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become involved in a study they don't even know about?
While researchers have strictly defined standards for off-line investigations, online data are available.
"I don't think that many users have at least thought that the researcher can observe their profiles," says Neil Selvin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a study he conducted in 2006 using the public pages of Facebook students.
"It was only between them and their friends as much as they imagined."
Then the question of methodology arises.
Even off-line there's no guarantee that the subject matter of the study is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is not possible to know how much information is available in the user's profile and on the user's page.
"What you say on Facebook, and what you do outside Facebook, two completely different things," says Selwin.
That is why, despite years of work in the field of technology, Selwyn thinks that the notebook and pen are still the best research tools available.
"There can be no substitute for getting out into a real world and communicating with real people," he says.
