The Court will approve “digital television” in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals for digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court (WB) rejected the constitutional claims put forward by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the Presidential Decree, which carries the so-called “digital television” from 2021 to 2015, as there were no eight votes required to cancel it.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Messa, considered that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his powers by issuing a decree detailing actions for the transition to digital ground television.
As a result, the constitutional claims made by the Senate were rejected owing to the absence of a qualified majority of the eight votes necessary for the court to speak on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree and remain in force.
The draft statement, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional because the regulation of the radio and television programme was a right enshrined by the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel) Act, in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margaret Moon and Sánchez Correro voted in favour of the project.
On this argument both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and to support complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions mentioned in it concerning the transition to digital broadcasting.
The Ministerial Meeting also decided to reject the demands of the Chamber of Deputies without having to discuss the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he disagreed with the project ' s arguments in the sense that the federal executive could not determine the general rules of action for which the public administration should prepare.
“I also don't think that, if it did, it would have an impact on regulatory autonomy” and recalled that public policy planning in strategic areas such as telecommunications was relevant to the federal executive branch, which has a constitutional mandate, State administration.
The conversion of analog signals to digital signals, one of the most important changes that have occurred in recent years, has resulted in better use of the radio-electronic spectrum, better quality of the signal and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would have meant postponing the benefits of conversion into digital form, which included meeting public needs, which had not only a technical dimension “because it covered economic, social, political and national security issues”.
These questions, he said, “require the whole system of State economic governance to include a group of authorities which the Constitution brings together into the State executive power”.
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the digital broadcasting exercise and had done so through the executive branch, despite the existence of specific technical institutions.
It cannot be concluded from this that the Government, in adopting the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competence of Congress, ensures administrative compliance with the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly, he said.
In Michoacán, the possibility of counting “voice by voice” is being analysed.
According to the data transmitted to the PRRA, the difference between the first and second seats in the Governorate's elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the 879 votes in the 6.074 protocols.
The possibility of counting “voting by voice” is real with regard to the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where the difference between the first and second seats in the Governor's elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the 879 votes in the total of 6.074 protocols.
In the light of this, Maria de Los Angeles Landeral Saragos, President of the General Council of the Council of the Institute for the Elections of Michoacán (IVM), recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the Electoral Corps had adopted a set of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
It should be recalled that Michoacán did not adopt the Constitution or the State Electoral Code or the Electoral Law Act, since the State Congress had approved reforms shortly before their entry into force in the electoral process, and Governor Leone ' s Year Book had not included his publication within the time frame stipulated in the Act in the Official Gazette of the State, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice (JJJJJ) ruled on the constitutional claim put forward by the local legislative assembly and called “unvalid and unlawful” the State Representative's voice on constitutional reform because he was not entitled “to permit or support them”.
In an interview on the possibility of “voting vote”, Maria de los Angeles Lianderal argued that, with the adoption of appropriate principles by the General Council, it would be possible to provide partial or full counting of votes by the local electoral body.
For example, partial recalculation of one or more ballot boxes may be made on the condition that: the results of the protocols do not coincide; there is no record of voting and counting of documents in the urn or not with the President; or where there are obvious errors or corrections in the record.
In addition, the overall conversion of votes in all ballot boxes may take place when there is an indication that the difference between the alleged winner candidate for the election and those who won the second seat is less than or equal to one per cent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a petition from the representative of the party and/or the coalition that presented the second candidate.
The total counting will also be done if the difference between the winner and the candidate who took the second seat is found to be less than or equal to one per cent, provided that there is a petition from the political party whose candidate has taken the second place, in the event that the ballot boxes have been excluded, which have been partially counted.
It is worth noting that such elections are held in Morelia, where, according to the ELV, the difference between the first and second seats is only 0.16 per cent, even excluding 129 votes out of a total of 923 Protocol votes.
