A new Italian Government will be formed on Wednesday
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monty, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to introduce a new Government that will face the crisis that has placed the country on the verge of economic catastrophe.
The Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monty, will meet on Wednesday with the President of Italy to introduce a new Government that will face a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic catastrophe and has damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the Presidential Palace said that Monty, who had been appointed on Sunday, would meet with the President, Giorgio Napolitano, on Wednesday, to confirm that he could form a government.
He is expected to present a Cabinet composed mainly of technocrats, although it is not clear when the new executive branch will take up its positions.
Monty said that he would present to the President the results of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a Government.
“I want to reaffirm my full confidence in our country's ability to get out of this difficult period”, said the former European Commissioner to reporters.
Monty did not expressly say that he had been able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
"It's now well marked," he said.
Monty has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, which is much less than usual, as Italy has faced a political and financial crisis that has brought their debt to a critical level
The administration, led by the former European Commissioner Monty, must approve the rigid economy package required by European leaders to regain confidence in Italy.
Based on the pressure on Monty to speed up, unstable markets have established income from Italian BTP bonds of 10 years more than 7 per cent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to save.
Emma Marchegalia, leader of the Italian Employers Federation, told reporters after meeting with Monty, "We said that we would actively support this government."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this critical situation.
Monty's prospects for success were largely based on the support of the LDP party Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday because of the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monty's efforts should lead to a good outcome," said reporters Angelino Alphaano, Secretary of the Centralist Law Party.
Support for LDP, the largest party in Italy, is important because so far many of its members have opposed the government majority of the technocrats that Monty is forming.
Parliamentary support
The new Government of Monty must have strong parliamentary support for reforms that are likely to be unpopular hard-saving reforms.
Any closure or suspension of these attempts may lead to a new and destructive attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks increased pressure to warn that Monty's failure could be a disaster.
Monty began his consultations on Monday with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women's organizations.
He'll finish his meetings Tuesday night.
Monty was appointed on Sunday, Napolitano, who allowed a rapid transition to respond to the crisis.
After a short break at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would retire, the value of Italy's debts had now reached a critical level in the face of uncertainty as to whether the new Prime Minister would succeed.
Saving Italy with a public debt of 1.8 billion euros would be too much for modern eurozone financial advocates.
Monty said that his Government would exist before the next elections for 2013, despite widespread forecasts that politicians would only give him time to reform before new elections were appointed.
Monty said that he would like to include politicians in his office, but the major parties insist that it should be composed only of technical specialists, a testament to the fact that the financial situation affects the process.
