The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect obesity in children and young people, which is called the protocol “Getics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescents”, which will calculate the weight-related signs.
In his statement, Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Medical Research Unit for Biochemistry of the National Medical Centre of the Twenty-first Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been assembled.
The team is assisted by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Health of the Nation (NIPH) and the Centre for Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
The study invites the population (whether prescribed or not) to participate in MSSI sports centres participating in the study to the Mexico Valley, where every Saturday, from 8:00 in the morning, tests involving children will be conducted.
He stressed that the protocol had begun to be maintained at the sports centre in Quautemoke (west of Mexico City) and that since 8 October the events were being held at the sports centre in Nesaualkootle, eastern Mexico.
Once the goal of attracting between 500 and 600 children has been achieved, the study will continue at the Sports Centre of Independence (South Mexico) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (North Mexico).
He explained that the purpose of the study was to understand the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors among children and young Mexicans to prevent chronic degenerative diseases.
On 14 November, the main objective will be to gather three thousand children and adolescents between the ages of 6 and 14 with parental permission and supervision to complete individual feeding questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and the history of family hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors leading to diseases such as diabetes or renal failure.
He explained that on Saturday, all participants (weight, growth and cover of the waist), blood pressure and glucose levels, fats, cholesterol and insulin and genetic analysis (to identify genes related to child obesity) would be measured.
Cruz Lopez said that the study reflected the concern of health professionals about the alarming increase in weight among children.
Medical studies carried out between 1999 and 2006 indicate that there has been an increase in just six years: in the case of boys, 77 per cent were obese, in the case of girls, 47 per cent; in the case of underweight, there has also been a significant increase,” said MSSI.
He said that the rationale for finding markers was based on the fact that the population was different from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that, on average, Mexicans were 65 per cent descendants of American Indians, 30 per cent of the descendants of Europeans and five per cent of the descendants of Africans, and this condition had an impact on the genes associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that the main consequence of obesity genetics is the body's inability to burn excess energy that we consume (calories) and it is put off in fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants was a comprehensive assessment of children, which could reveal whether they had any level of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the existence of dark folds on the neck (aractants) and forearms means the possibility of a violation of metabolicism and even prediabeticism.
The information is treated confidentially, and the doctors transmit it in writing to the parents to whom they explain all the measures and changes in the way of life that must be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main causes of overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: sedentary lifestyles, or lack of daily physical activity, most of the day at home in front of television, and use of transportation on small distances instead of walking.
This is also due to the high consumption of calories, i.e. the increased use of sweet drinks and carbohydrates (tales, bread, pizzas, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetic predisposition analysed in this programme.
UNAM asphalt can avoid cracks
Raphael Herrera, a study at UNAM School of Chemistry, developed polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of best quality resistant to the environment and temperature.
If the signals sent by road coverage were to be taken into account, it would be necessary to repair some 200,000 pits for each rainy season in the Mehiko Valley, says Rafael Herrera Naher, a chemical researcher at UNAM, and adds that if the construction and maintenance of asphalted road surface were to be regulated, the number of pits could be reduced or reduced to zero.
In his lecture, the Technical View of Measles, which was read in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, reported that the laboratory for which he was responsible was developing polymer-moderated battoms for the production of a mixture of bitumen, but with a better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some towns in the north, to improve the quality of roads and thus prevent the formation of pits.
He explained that bitum, the heavyest part of oil is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some a high molecular mass called asphaltones, and others a low molecular mass called malformations, which together give road coverage its characteristic viscous behaviour.
The viscosity of the bitumen is that at a high temperature of about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it maintains an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures it becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance to street asphalt is not permanent, but changes over the course of the day, depending on the natural conditions and temperature, said a chemical engineer.
He noted that Mexico City’s streets were largely covered with a flexible cover made of six layers of material, the last three of which included bitumen.
Among the upper layers is a bitumen made up of small stones, dropped into bitumen and then compressed.
Every stone that makes up this surface, he says, is sunk in bitumen.
When moving vehicles and applying force, this helps the forces to be very well distributed on the road surface.
If it were modified asphalt, they would be better distributed, said a chemical engineer.
On the asphalt floor, he added, was placed by the last layer, called the wear layer, made out of a small stone, actually sand, also loaded into asphalt.
Since this layer will be in contact with the wheels of transport, it must be more resistant than asphalt and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and disseminate these efforts, wear and tear also requires appropriate thickness, and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
The weather, especially humidity and temperature declines, were also very important factors for consideration, especially water, he said, because it had a significant impact on asphalt.
When the land is raw, the water enters the surface and is difficult to get out of it, causing every layer of surface to be softened and thus creating a hole.
When creating a hole, he said, the first one was worn out and only then affected bitumen, but the damage did not happen instantly, which should be taken into account in the first signs of ongoing repair programmes.
A member of the National Research System explained that transport is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer of surface must always be related to the transport load and must be guaranteed to ensure that this requirement is met in order to prevent the frequent appearance of holes.
Raphael Herrera said that relatively bitumen still had much to study and do, for example, bitumen emulsions, which in other countries were already on the market and even helped to make pits with ease and without the use of high temperatures.
